Basics

Strings - R understands both single and double quotes for strings.

BE VERY CAREFUL if you decide to use single quotes. It’ll fuck up in a lot of strings

‘this is Dave’s dog’, for instance, will fall over. Stick to double quotes in most instances!

employees <- tibble(
  first_name = c("Sally", "steven", "Mary", "John"),
  last_name = c("Smith", "hasTings", "Milne", "Davidson"),
  postcode = c("EH10 6GH", "EH3 7HL", "G1 7FR", NA), 
  location = c(" ", "Edinburgh", "", "Stirling")
)

employees

Strings can contain any sort of character. Different numbers of spaces are all unique strings, and one space is not the same as an empty string!

employees %>% 
  group_by(location) %>% 
  summarise(count = n())
mary_location <- employees %>% 
  filter(first_name == "Mary") %>% 
  select(location) %>% 
  pull()

sally_location <- employees %>% 
  filter(first_name == "Sally") %>% 
  select(location) %>% 
  pull()

mary_location == sally_location
[1] FALSE

Time for stringr

concatenate strings with two functions: str_c str_join

str_c("This","is","some","text","that","I","wanttojoin")
[1] "ThisissometextthatIwanttojoin"
employees %>% 
  mutate(full_name = str_c(first_name, last_name, sep=' '))
employees %>% 
  mutate(full_name = str_c(first_name, location, sep=' '))

Casings

pangram <- " Todays class is about basics of string"

pangram %>% 
  str_to_sentence()
[1] " Todays class is about basics of string"
employees %>% 
  select(first_name, last_name) %>% 
  mutate(first_name_fixed = str_to_title(first_name)) %>% 
  mutate(last_name_fixed = str_to_title(last_name))

Splitting

unbroken_string <- "Al is going to help me with this part"
unbroken_string %>% 
  str_split(" ") %>% 
  flatten_chr()
[1] "Al"    "is"    "going" "to"    "help"  "me"    "with"  "this"  "part" 
employees %>% 
  mutate(postcode_new = str_split(postcode, " ")) %>% 
  unnest(postcode_new)

Better to use separate() for something like this

employees %>% 
  separate(postcode, c("postcode_outer", "postcode_inner"), sep = " ")

Task - 10 mins Concatenate the strings “Manipulating” “strings” “is” “fun!” Capitalise the result and save it in a new variable Split the formatted string into individual characters

string_sentence <- str_c("Manipulating", "strings","is","fun!", sep = " ") %>% 
  str_to_sentence()

string_sentence
[1] "Manipulating strings is fun!"
str_split(string_sentence, "")
[[1]]
 [1] "M" "a" "n" "i" "p" "u" "l" "a" "t" "i" "n" "g" " " "s" "t" "r" "i" "n" "g" "s" " " "i" "s"
[24] " " "f" "u" "n" "!"

You can pull out pieces of strings with str_sub()

full_string <-  "let's find us a substring for this activity"
full_string
[1] "let's find us a substring for this activity"
full_string %>% 
  str_sub(start = 1, end = 5)
[1] "let's"
full_string %>% 
  str_sub(start = 5)
[1] "s find us a substring for this activity"

You can use a negative on start to count backwards, if you wanted the last characters instead. Useful for stuff like postcodes which start with either 3 or 4 characters but always end with 3.

full_string %>% 
  str_sub(start = -5)
[1] "ivity"
employees %>% 
  mutate(postcode_outer = str_sub(postcode, 1, -4)) %>% 
  mutate(postcode_inner = str_sub(postcode, -3))
original_string <- "lets have some words that we will be replacing now"
str_sub(original_string, 1, 22) <- "I have some"
original_string
[1] "I have somehat we will be replacing now"
number <- 123456.8
number
[1] 123456.8
number2 <- 1234567.8
number2
[1] 1234568

Task - 10 mins Here are some more questions for you to practice with. Remember, the point of these questions is not to do something that makes sense for this dataset, but rather to allow you to practice using the techniques we’ve learnt today on a real dataset. When it comes to your projects, you will be in charge of deciding how to work with the strings in your dataset. We are going to use some Spotify data for this task: spotify_songs <- read_csv(“data/spotify_sample.csv”) Upcase the text in the playlist_name column. Overwrite the existing column to store the result. Lowcase the text in the track_artist column. Store the result in a new column called track_artist_lowcase. Take the first 5 characters of the playlist_id column, and save it in a new column called playlist_start. Take the first 4 characters of the track_album_release_date column and save it in a new column called year. What else can you do to this dataset to practice? Can you work with the numbers? This is open ended - have fun!

spotify_songs <- read_csv("data/spotify_sample.csv")
New names:Rows: 1000 Columns: 25── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Delimiter: ","
chr (10): track_id, track_name, track_artist, track_album_id, track_album_name, track_album_...
dbl (15): ...1, X1, track_popularity, danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, speechiness...
ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
spotify_songs %>% 
  mutate(playlist_name = str_to_upper(playlist_name),
         track_artist_lowcase = str_to_lower(track_artist),
         playlist_start = str_sub(playlist_id, end = 5),
         year = str_sub(track_album_release_date, end = 4))

Regular Expressions

single_string <- "string a"
strings <- c("string a", "string b", "string c", "string d", "striiiiiiing e")

Is this pattern present in a string? Use str_detect()

pattern <- "word"

single_string %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1] FALSE
strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
pattern <- "str"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1] TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE TRUE
pattern <- "string"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)

You can use square brackets to denote a range of individual characters

pattern <- "[abc]"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE

You can use a hyphen to donate real ranges like a to c

pattern <- "[A-C]"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

It’s worth nothing here that with regard to expressions, the letters of the alphabet are store Upper Case and then Lower Case, so you can do stuff like [A-z] to match every character, but [a-Z] doesn’t work.

You can also use (?i) as a mode modifier to ignore case.

pattern <- "(?i)[A-Z]"
pattern2 <- "(?i)[a-z]"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern2)

Another one is i{n} for number of repeated occurences

pattern <- "i{3}"

strings %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE

Task - 15 mins

Make a vector containing the following strings: - “We’re having great fun learning about data analysis at CodeClan!” - “CodeClan is at 37 Castle Terrace in Edinburgh and ClockWise in Glasgow” - “Our cohort code starts with DE or DR” - “You get a great view of the castle or the national conservatoire from just outside CodeClan’s door”

Write and test regular expressions which will match: - Any string mentioning CodeClan - Any string containing two consecutive capital letters - Any string not including the word “castle” or “Castle”

Hint Remember, str_detect() can take an optional third argument called negate

Hint The techniques we looked at above can be combined.

task_vector <-  c("We're having great fun learning about data analysis at CodeClan!",
                "CodeClan is at 37 Castle Terrace in Edinburgh and Clockwise in Glasgow",
                "Our cohort code starts with DE or DR",
                "You get a great view of the castle or the national conservatoire from just outside CodeClan's door")
str_test_codeclan <- "CodeClan"
str_test_cons_caps <- "[:upper:][:upper:]"
str_test_castle <- "(?i)castle"

task_vector %>% 
  str_detect(str_test_codeclan)
task_vector %>% 
  str_detect(str_test_cons_caps)
task_vector %>% 
  str_detect(str_test_castle, negate = TRUE)

Extracting matching sub-strings

Uses str_extract()

strings <- c(
  "This string has an_address@email.com in it", 
  "This one has user.name@company.co.uk", 
  "Now we've got other_person_123@server.net and my.name@runningoutofideas.com"
)

By default just extracts the first match that returns TRUE

pattern <- "[a-z]"

strings %>% 
  str_extract(pattern)
[1] "h" "h" "o"
string <- "@emailprovider.com"
pattern <- "[a-z]*@emailprovider.com"

string %>% 
  str_detect(pattern)
[1] TRUE

This uses the * quantifier.

Quantifiers

  • = any number of
  • = one or more {x} = specific number of
pattern <- "[A-z]+@"

strings %>% 
  str_extract(pattern)
[1] "an_address@" "name@"       "name@"

[:alnum:] is a POSIX for all alphanumerics

pattern <- "[:alnum:]+@"

strings %>% 
  str_extract(pattern)
pattern <- "[:alnum:]+@[:alnum:]+"

strings %>%
  str_extract(pattern)
[1] "address@email" "name@company"  "123@server"

You can use str_extract_all to pull all occurrences.

pattern <- "[a-z0-9_\\.]+@[a-z0-9_\\.]+"

strings %>%
  str_extract_all(pattern)
[[1]]
[1] "an_address@email.com"

[[2]]
[1] "user.name@company.co.uk"

[[3]]
[1] "other_person_123@server.net"   "my.name@runningoutofideas.com"

str_replace

pattern <- "[a-z0-9_\\.]+@[a-z0-9_\\.]+"

strings %>% 
  str_replace_all(pattern, "REDACTED")
[1] "This string has REDACTED in it"      "This one has REDACTED"              
[3] "Now we've got REDACTED and REDACTED"

Anchors

^ start $ end

test_strings <- c(
  "abc", 
  "Abc",
  "abC",
  "s"
)
# extract all lowercase letters
test_strings %>% 
  str_extract_all("[a-z]")
[[1]]
[1] "a" "b" "c"

[[2]]
[1] "b" "c"

[[3]]
[1] "a" "b"

[[4]]
[1] "s"
#extract the lowercase letter if it is the last letter in the string
test_strings %>% 
  str_extract_all("[a-z]$")
[[1]]
[1] "c"

[[2]]
[1] "c"

[[3]]
character(0)

[[4]]
[1] "s"
#extract the lowercase letter if it is the first letter in the string
test_strings %>% 
  str_extract_all("^[a-z]")
[[1]]
[1] "a"

[[2]]
character(0)

[[3]]
[1] "a"

[[4]]
[1] "s"
#extract the lowercase letters if they are the first AND last letters in the string
test_strings %>% 
  str_extract_all("^[a-z]$")
[[1]]
character(0)

[[2]]
character(0)

[[3]]
character(0)

[[4]]
[1] "s"

Strings within a tibble

student <- c("Abigail", "Bjorn", "Caitlin")
age <- c(25, 56, 40)
emails <- c("abigal12@company.co.uk", "bsmith@gmail.co.uk", "caitlin_1980")

student_info <- tibble(student, age, emails)

student_info 
student_info %>%
  mutate(email_detect = (str_detect(emails, "[a-z]+@")))
